  <!-- Quick answer -->
  <article class="premium-card mt-10" id="quick-answer">
    <div class="premium-card-inner">
      <h2 class="font-bold text-2xl text-gray-900 mb-6">The 20-Second Answer</h2>
      <div class="p-6 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-r from-indigo-50 via-purple-50 to-pink-50 border-l-4 border-indigo-500 mb-6">
        <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">
          <strong class="text-indigo-600">GB counts in thousands; GiB counts in 1,024s.</strong> 1 GB = 1,000³ bytes = 1,000,000,000. 1 GiB = 1,024³ bytes = 1,073,741,824. The gibibyte is <strong>7.4% bigger</strong>, so the same data always looks like a <em>smaller number</em> in GiB. Drive makers count in GB (correctly); Windows counts in GiB but prints "GB" (confusingly). That labeling mismatch is the entire mystery.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div class="p-5 rounded-2xl bg-gradient-to-br from-teal-50 to-white border border-teal-100 text-center">
          <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-teal-600 mb-1">Gigabyte (GB) — decimal</p>
          <p class="text-2xl font-extrabold text-gray-900">1,000,000,000</p>
          <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-1">bytes = 1,000 × 1,000 × 1,000</p>
        </div>
